Treap 

Surprise! You’ve just landed a role at CFAANG working on credit card fraud detection. Every second, thousands of transaction values are processed, inserted, and removed from your system. Analysts need to quickly understand the distribution of these transactions in real time.

To handle this efficiently, you decide to use a Treap-based data structure.

Assume that basic Treap operations (INSERT, DELETE, and SEARCH) are already implemented.

Your task is to extend this structure to support the following additional operations:

KTH k
Return the k-th smallest element currently in the set.

COUNT x
Return the number of elements less than or equal to x.

RANGE l r
Return the number of elements in the interval [l, r].

Requirements

All of these operations must run in O(logn) time
You must extend the treap properly by storing additional information as needed in each node.
this may require you do modify the following functions:

insertion
deletion
split
merge 
Input

The first line contains an integer Q (1 ≤ Q ≤ 2 × 10⁵), the number of operations.

Each of the next Q lines contains one operation of the following form:

INSERT x
DELETE x
SEARCH x
KTH k
COUNT x
RANGE l r

x, l, r are integers in the range [0, 10⁹]

1 ≤ k ≤ current size of the set of nodes

You may assume all inserted values are unique

Output

For each query operation, output the result on its own line:

SEARCH x, output true or false
KTH k, output the k-th smallest element
COUNT x, output an integer
RANGE l r, output an integer

Example
Input
8
INSERT 5
INSERT 3
INSERT 7
KTH 2
COUNT 5
RANGE 3 7
DELETE 5
KTH 2
Output
5
2
3
7

Notes
Efficient solutions must use a Treap or another balanced data structure, naive or brute force solutions will fail
You will need to add to every node additional metadata to support faster queries